The 45-year-old’s final game in charge was Villa’s 10th Premier League match without a win and came after more supporter protests. Fans have wanted him out for weeks, frustrated by a lack of points, goals and style.

The trip to Hull was their 15th league match of the season without scoring. Christian Benteke, Ron Vlaar and Tom Cleverley — considered three of the better players — were left on the bench. Villa supporters unveiled a ‘Lambert Out’ banner.

His departure came on the day the Birmingham Mail called for Villa to immediately axe the Scot with a piece entitled: ‘Birmingham Mail says: Lambert must go!’

But it comes a fortnight after Villa chief executive Tom Fox insisted they would not bow to fan pressure. Tim Sherwood and Jurgen Klinsmann are two of the early contenders to take over. 

